i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wallur","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>waler</i>, <i>waliere</i>, <i>walour</i>, <i>waller</i> ‘builder of walls, mason’.","English: in Sussex, perhaps a topographic name for someone who lived by a prominent wall.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>waller</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>walle</i>, Old English <i>wælle</i>, <i>wælle</i>. It is a West Midlands dialect form of   Weller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallar","meanings":["English: variant of   Waller  ."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Hendrik","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Henrik ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hendrik de Wallur was born on 6 May 1156, in Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England as the son of Johan de Wallur. He had at least 1 son. He died on 10 November 1200, in his hometown, at the age of 44, and was buried in Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"6 May 1156–10 November 1200":"6. mai 1156–10. november 1200","1156–1200":"1156–1200","1187–1274":"1187–1274","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","6 May 1156":"6. mai 1156","10 November 1200":"10. november 1200","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","1187":"1187","after 10 November 1200":"pärast 10. novembrit 1200","1274":"1274","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"6 May 1156–10 November 1200":"6. toukokuuta 1156–10. marraskuuta 1200","1156–1200":"1156–1200","1187–1274":"1187–1274","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","6 May 1156":"6. toukokuuta 1156","10 November 1200":"10. marraskuuta 1200","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","1187":"1187","after 10 November 1200":"10. marraskuuta 1200 jälkeen","1274":"1274","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"6 May 1156–10 November 1200":"6 mai 1156–10 novembre 1200","1156–1200":"1156–1200","1187–1274":"1187–1274","1125–Male":"1125–Décédé","6 May 1156":"6 mai 1156","10 November 1200":"10 novembre 1200","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","1187":"1187","after 10 November 1200":"après 10 novembre 1200","1274":"1274","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Hendrik de Wallur est né le 6 mai 1156, à Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, fils de Johan de Wallur. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé le 10 novembre 1200, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 44 ans, et a été